textBeforeTable: Out of 150 entries, the following students were honored for their submissions: The purpose of the contest was to encourage children in grades 4 through 8 to learn about New Jersey's fish. Each student had to submit original artwork that depicted a New Jersey fish in its habitat along with a short bibliography of the species. The winners' artwork will be on display at the Pequest Trout Hatchery through the end of April and can also be viewed on the Division's website at www.njfishandwildlife.com. After fishing, the winners received plaques and fishing equipment at an awards luncheon held in the facility's auditorium. New Jersey Council of Trout Unlimited sponsored the awards, luncheon and fishing equipment. "This is certainly one of the most enjoyable activities I have the pleasure to participate in," McDowell said. "It is a credit to the parents of these youngsters to have instilled in their children the values and appreciation of nature that inspire them to create such fine work." Assistant Commissioner Cari Wild of DEP's Natural and Historic Resources and Division Director Bob McDowell were also on hand to spend time fishing with the youngsters.
